**Uniqueness.** Suppose that $\mathfrak{a}=\mathfrak{p}_{1}\cdot\cdot\cdot\mathfrak{p}_{r}=\mathfrak{p}_{1}^{\prime}\cdot\cdot\cdot\mathfrak{p}_{s}^{\prime}$ are two factorizations of $\mathfrak{a}$. Then, $\mathfrak{p}_{1}^{\prime} \supseteq \mathfrak{p}_{1}\cdot\cdot\cdot\mathfrak{p}_{r}$ so $\mathfrak{p}_{1}^{\prime} \supseteq \mathfrak{p}_{i}$, for some $i$, say $\mathfrak{p}_{1}^{\prime} \supseteq \mathfrak{p}_{1}$. $\mathfrak{p}_{1}$ is maximal, so $\mathfrak{p}_{1}^{\prime}=\mathfrak{p}_{1}$. Thus, multiplying both sides by $(\mathfrak{p}_{1}^{\prime})^{-1}$ and cancelling using $(\mathfrak{p}_{1}^{\prime})^{-1}\mathfrak{p}_{1}^{\prime}=\mathcal{O}_{K}$, we obtain $\mathfrak{p}_{2}^{\prime}\cdot\cdot\cdot\mathfrak{p}_{s}^{\prime}=\mathfrak{p}_{2}\cdot\cdot\cdot\mathfrak{p}_{r}$. Thus, continuing in this way, we see that $r=s$ and the primes are unique up to reordering.

